    "instruction": "From metric.csv, filter rows where cmdb_id is one of [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service] AND timestamp is within the incident window 2024-01-23 11:59:43 to 2024-01-23 12:29:43 UTC. For each group (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_where_value>global_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC) (if any), max_value_in_window, and the previously-computed global p95 threshold (use the p95 values computed from the full series). Return a compact table with columns [cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value, p95], sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value desc, limited to top 20 rows. If no anomalies detected for any group, return an empty table message."
}

{
    "analysis": "We detected multiple metric anomalies (mostly memory and diskio, plus some cpu/socket/workload) across several candidate services (ts-travel-service, ts-order-service, ts-train-service, ts-route-service, ts-auth-service) during the incident window. Earliest metric anomaly appears at 2024-01-23 12:02:00 UTC and anomalies are scattered through ~12:25 UTC. Multiple services have points exceeding their global P95 thresholds, so we need traces to determine which faulty service is downstream (most likely root cause) in call chains. Next, we must analyze traces related to these candidate services to see which service calls show abnormal error_rate or increased duration during the incident window.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv, select trace_name rows that include any of these service identifiers: 'ts-auth-service', 'ts-order-service', 'ts-route-service', 'ts-train-service', 'ts-travel-service' (match anywhere in trace_name). For each matching trace_name compute global-series aggregates using the full available trace.csv: count, p50, p90, p95, max_value. Then filter those matching trace_name rows to the incident window 2024-01-23 11:59:43 to 2024-01-23 12:29:43 UTC and compute anomaly_count where value > global_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp in the window (if any), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table with columns [trace_name, count, p50, p90, p95, max_value, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window], sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis shows repeated spikes in row_count and increased durations targeting several services. Notably: trace.to_ts-order-service.* has the largest anomaly count (earliest at 2024-01-23 12:02:00 UTC), and trace.to_ts-travel-service.* and trace.from_ts-travel-service.* show large row_count and duration spikes starting ~12:03 UTC. Metric anomalies also show memory and disk I/O breaches across ts-travel-service, ts-order-service, ts-train-service, ts-route-service, and ts-auth-service during the window. Because multiple service-level components are faulty, we must use logs to further disambiguate which service shows traffic/error symptoms consistent with being the downstream root cause. Specifically, check per-service log features (log.row_count and log.error_count) for the five candidate services in the incident window versus their global P95 thresholds to see which service had the strongest log-level anomalies (earliest and most severe).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From log.csv, filter rows where cmdb_id is one of [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service]. For each group (cmdb_id, log_name) compute global statistics from the full available series: count, p50, p90, p95. Then restrict to the incident window 2024-01-23 11:59:43 to 2024-01-23 12:29:43 UTC and compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count_where_value>global_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window (if any), and max_value_in_window. Return a compact table with columns [cmdb_id, log_name, count, p50, p90, p95, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window], sorted by anomaly_count desc then max_value_in_window desc, limited to top 20 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We have identified metric-level faults across multiple candidate services (mem, diskio, cpu, socket, workload breaches for ts-travel-service, ts-order-service, ts-train-service, ts-route-service, ts-auth-service). Trace analysis shows repeated spikes in row_count and increased durations targeting order-service (earliest anomalies ~12:02:00 UTC, highest anomaly count) and travel-service (earliest ~12:03:00 UTC, very large row_count spikes). Log analysis shows elevated log.row_count (traffic spikes) for travel, route, order, and auth; log.error_count shows no anomalies. According to the rules, when multiple service-level faults exist we should use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service in call chains. To do that, we need a compact per-service summary of trace anomalies (aggregate anomaly counts and earliest anomaly times across all trace features that reference each service) so we can determine which faulty service is downstream and earliest/most severe in traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv do the following: 1) Consider trace_name rows that mention any of the candidate services [ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service] (match anywhere in trace_name). 2) For each matching trace_name compute the global p95 from the full available series (no time filtering). 3) Then filter the trace rows to the incident window 2024-01-23 11:59:43 to 2024-01-23 12:29:43 UTC and count anomaly points where value > that trace_name's global p95; record the earliest anomaly timestamp for that trace_name and the max value in-window. 4) Aggregate results per service (extract service name from trace_name by looking for 'to_ts-<service>' or 'from_ts-<service>' and mapping to the underlying service name): compute total_trace_anomaly_count (sum of anomaly counts across its trace_names), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum across its trace_names), and max_value_in_window_across_traces. 5) Return a compact table with columns [service, total_trace_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window_across_traces], sorted by total_trace_anomaly_count desc, limited to the five candidate services."
}

Review summary: multiple services showed spikes, but ts-travel-service exhibited the largest aggregated trace anomalies, large row_count and duration spikes, and breaches in resource metrics (notably disk I/O). This points to ts-travel-service experiencing resource pressure from a traffic surge, with disk I/O being the dominant observable bottleneck.

